howPublicProfile?language=EN>Tuwene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Beware the paladin<br>with a map & a plan</span><br>  Posts: 112<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/11/02 2:17:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=8>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> Cogito is right.<br><br>He was held for over a month with no rights except POW status while they debated whether or not to revoke his citizenship.  It was decided it'd be too tough to revoke it (statues for that are pretty severe) so they had to leave him a US citizen -- once that was established, sadly, US law has to apply to him and he's given rights.<br><br>FUcker should be someone's bitch in a cuban prison right now, and they tried, but it didn't work out -- believe me, there is/was no popular support here in the states for the guy to get special treatment, and in the long run he'll probably end up worse off. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uarleanna.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arleanna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Send me a tell in game!</span><br>  Posts: 219<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/11/02 8:47:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://people.ne.mediaone.net/pretzhere/EQ/Sphynx4.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> Seems like it would be pretty hard to revoke citizenship for someone who was born in America. Not like he has another country willing to accept him as their citizen. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=61467">Arleanna Mistmoore</a><BR><a href="http://www.The-Elitists.com">The Elitists and Vagrants</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ucogito.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cogito</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lord of the Whacky Woondarland</span><br>  Posts: 1771<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/11/02 9:47:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://voxton.freewebspace.com/sigs/strangelove.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> I think this was discussed here earlier, and it seems there are some acts that can cause you to lose your citizenship. Joining an enemy's armed forces is apparently one of them. It is unusual, but there is such a thing as a person without citizenship in ANY country. <br><br>It's unusual, just like getting charged (let alone) convicted with treason in the US... Since the founding fathers effetively committed treason by signing the Declaration of Independence, and with that in mind, they made it very, very hard for someone to get nailed on that charge. <br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uarleanna.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arleanna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Send me a tell in game!</span><br>  Posts: 220<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 1:35:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://people.ne.mediaone.net/pretzhere/EQ/Sphynx4.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> He wasn't in a foreign country's army though. I know it's a technicality, but legal cases are built around this kinda thing. So I don't think they could have got him on that unless the Taliban was actually recognized by the US. It's like me joining a radical Mexican group's &quot;army&quot;. Just because they claim to rule the country ligitamitely doesn't mean the US will recognize that legitimacy.<br><br>So what other reason could they revoke citizenship? Again, remembering he is natural born US citizen, the Taliban was never recognized, and he has no country willing to declare him as a citizen. It makes for a good story to read about &quot;The Man Without a Country&quot;, but I don't think it's actualy possible. What do you think? <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=61467">Arleanna Mistmoore</a><BR><a href="http://www.The-Elitists.com">The Elitists and Vagrants</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ucogito.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cogito</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lord of the Whacky Woondarland</span><br>  Posts: 1772<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 2:57:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://voxton.freewebspace.com/sigs/strangelove.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> I think I'm not entirely sure what I'm talking about <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . And I don't like to pretend that I know more than I do, so lemme say, that this is just not-well informed speculation... <br><br>You may well be correct, that he needs to be part of an officially recognized government's army, in order to lose his citizenship. It does make sense. <br><br>My knee-jerk reaction was based on the fact that he was actively fighting US forces. Now, you could say that about protesters in the 60s. But in this case, US forces were engaged in combat, with an enemy. And the words of the law (as far as I remember) basically covered anyone who fought by their side -- even those who provided aid for them (which would cover medical aid, as far as I know. The exception of course is pows, and the main point about that situation, is that pows are no longer combatants). <br><br>That is of course, just speculation. <br><br>More speculation: I think that although there may be a legal case for removing his citizenship, it would quite simply seem a tad too draconian, to be honest. It'd be a bad PR situation, simply. In a country where free speach is such a profound, integral part of its fabric, I think this lunatic/asshole/traitor/fuck might be viewed -- today, or down the road -- as someone who simply protested his country's actions, and used his first amendment rights, although in an extreme way. The fact that there is no known evidence of him actually engaging in combat with US troops -- let alone killing anyone, as well as the fact that he was captured, would aid the 'pity' factor to his case. <br><br>So, although I'm sure there are a lot of mistakes made, the decision to not remove his citizenship MIGHT be a case of caution, and PR issues. <br><br>But i dunno.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uelcheproudfoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Elche Proudfoot</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mmmmm lobster</span><br>  Posts: 500<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 6:31:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://images.about.com/specials/service/promotion/sod/male_lead_stealer/josh_ryan_evans.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> so we should just return all the detainees who are citizens of other states? <p><font size="-2" face="verdana">Elche Proudfoot<BR><b>Founder and Chief Mystic</font><br><font color=red size="-2" face="verdana"> Shining Path</FONT></b> </FONT></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uarleanna.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arleanna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Send me a tell in game!</span><br>  Posts: 222<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 12:00:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://people.ne.mediaone.net/pretzhere/EQ/Sphynx4.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> Good points. I guess what I'm getting at is: Is it possible to revoke citizenship when that person has &quot;nowhere to land&quot; so to speak? If his citizenship were revoked and no one would take him in where does he go? <br><br>Say he was placed in jail and citizenship revoked (can you even detain a person without a country?) when he finally gets out of jail where does he go? He can't even get a passport. Just wondering and all. Too bad there isn't someone from the state department playing on our server, eh? <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=61467">Arleanna Mistmoore</a><BR><a href="http://www.The-Elitists.com">The Elitists and Vagrants</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/utrainwreckjm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Trainwreck jm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 163<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 1:17:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> There's a dude who was living in the Paris airport for like 2 years because no country would accept him. i believe he was of Iranian origin. <br><br>don't know if he's still there... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ucogito.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cogito</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lord of the Whacky Woondarland</span><br>  Posts: 1774<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 1:21:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://voxton.freewebspace.com/sigs/strangelove.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> I believe it is possible to revoke citizenship, and leave a person without citizenship. This would essentially leave the individual stranded: he'd become an illegal alien, except there would be no homeland where he could be deported to. <br><br>However, the effect of such a &quot;homelessness&quot; would vary greatly, depending on the location they are at, when it happened. <br><br>For instance, there have been cases where people in third world countries have flown on commercial flights to western countries, hoping to live on social welfare. However, they do not have status as any sort of refugees, so they would be rejected, but they destroy their passports en route. When they land, they are in a limbo -- they will not be allowed to enter the country, but cannot be sent back. <br><br>In fact, there is a fairly famous case of an asian traveller who has been stuck in an airport in France for several years. I dont' remember what the details were, but something went wrong -- he never intentionally destroyed his papers, but he might have been allowed to board a flight by mistake, without having the correct immigration papers. He's been given the opportunity to enter a couple of different countries, but he wants to go to England -- but they will not allow him there. So he's stuck. The guy is some kinda celebrity, goes to the bathrooms in the morning, washes up, then sits around in the no-man's land of the airport all day, receiving money or food from travellers who know him. Weird stuff. <br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/utrainwreckjm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Trainwreck jm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 164<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 1:27:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> Here's something on that. Looks like he got out in 1999... after <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 11 f-ing YEARS</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->!<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> An Iranian asylum-seeker Leaves French airport after 11-year stay</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><br>The strange and agonizing story of one of the most famous asylum-seekers in the world has ended after 11 years.  In early July, the Iranian Kareem Nasser Miran finally received permission to seek asylum in Belgium.   Travel documents issued by the Belgian Refugee Commission allow Miran to leave the French Charles de Gaulle Airport where he has been living for over a decade.  Although it is not unusual for asylum-seekers to wait that long for travel documents, Miran is the only asylum-seeker known to have spent the waiting period living on an airport bench.  He was originally stranded in the Paris airport during a transit between England and Belgium when he lost his Belgian travel documents and both countries refused him entry without papers. <br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ugrozzer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grozzer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 9:08:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> so we should just return all the detainees who are citizens of other states?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Duh. Elche, you have really lost it.<br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Australia (like the UK) committed special forces, naval vessels and aircraft to the war effort against the Taliban/Al Qaeda. We are on your side.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>i.e. If there's a difference between US nationals (John Walker Lindh) and, say, Chechen nationals, then there's a difference between Australian nationals and Chechen nationals. We fought the war by your side. The US should trust its allies.<br><br>Telling us he will only be handed over &quot;if Australia guarantees he will receive the maximum sentence&quot; goes against every principle of both the US and Australian legal systems.<br><br>It's really disturbing to see people accepting this crap as &quot;necessary measures&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uradgen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Radgen</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 9:49:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/Radgen5.jpg height=150 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Strange rules</span><hr size=1> Grozzer you missed the point.  Lindh is getting this treatnment DESPITE what most Americans including our law makers would like to see.  Most of us would be happy to have his ass rotting in Cuba with the rest.  However as a US citizen (and it is very hard to forcibly strip a native born citizen of his citizenship)he has certain rights that alien nationals in our control do not have. <br><br>And yes Austrailia did commit forces to this effort, but it WAS US soil that was attacked.   Think about this for a second.  Of all the Taliban/Al Queda forces that were involved, we only detained a couple hundred.  There is a reason for that.  We only detained those that are thought to A. have intelligence we can use, or B. were to dangerous to allow to go free.<br><br>Austrailia has a right to voice an opinion about how its citizens are treated (as does any other country) however once outside your borders (and this goes for the US as well) there is a limit to what a country can demeand of another country in relation to its citizens.<br><br>The US was the one attacked, we now have in detention persons who were associated with the organization that commited that attack.  No matter thier country of origin we have every right to treat those individuals as such with in the bounds of international law.  <br><br>Lindh is an exception because of our laws and constitution.  There is little we can do about that as much as we would like too.     <br><br>And I never really herad that the demand was for these people to recieve the maximum sentance.  The demand I heard was an assurance that they would be dealt with appropriately by thier countires of origin if repatriated.  Considering some of them come from Chenya and Yemen, pretty chaotic places at best, this is not an unreasonable demand. <p><center><font face="lucida handwriting, arial" color="006800" size=+2><b>Radgen Waldjaeger</font></b><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="675f00" size=+1><b>Pathfinder of Karana</font><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="blue" size=+1>Shining Path</font></b><br><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/tiger_run_md_clr.gif></center></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showPrevMessage?topicID=97.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showNextMessage?topicID=97.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=19><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/addReply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.emailToFriend?topicID=97.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.threadControl?topicID=97.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=97.topic>Su